<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="NAME"
>NAME <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>Apache::Status - Embedded interpreter status information</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="SYNOPSIS"
>SYNOPSIS <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<pre class="sh_perl"> &#60;Location /perl-status&#62;
 SetHandler  perl-script
 PerlHandler Apache::Status
 &#60;/Location&#62;</pre>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="DESCRIPTION"
>DESCRIPTION <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>The <b>Apache::Status</b> module provides some information about the status of the Perl interpreter embedded in the server.</p>

<p>Configure like so:</p>

<pre class="sh_perl"> &#60;Location /perl-status&#62;
 SetHandler  perl-script
 PerlHandler Apache::Status
 &#60;/Location&#62;</pre>

<p>Other modules can &#34;plugin&#34; a menu item like so:</p>

<pre class="sh_perl"> Apache::Status-&#62;menu_item(
    &#39;DBI&#39; =&#62; &#34;DBI connections&#34;, #item for Apache::DBI module
    sub {
        my($r,$q) = @_; #request and CGI objects
        my(@strings);
        push @strings,  &#34;blobs of html&#34;;
        return \@strings;     #return an array ref
    }
 ) if Apache-&#62;module(&#34;Apache::Status&#34;); #only if Apache::Status is loaded</pre>

<p><b>WARNING</b>: Apache::Status must be loaded before these modules via the PerlModule or PerlRequire directives.</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="OPTIONS"
>OPTIONS <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<dl>
<dt><a name="StatusOptionsAll"
>StatusOptionsAll</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>This single directive will enable all of the options described below.</p>

<pre class="sh_perl"> PerlSetVar StatusOptionsAll On</pre>

<dt><a name="StatusDumper"
>StatusDumper</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>When browsing symbol tables, the values of arrays, hashes ans calars can be viewed via <b>Data::Dumper</b> if this configuration variable is set to On:</p>

<pre class="sh_perl"> PerlSetVar StatusDumper On</pre>

<dt><a name="StatusPeek"
>StatusPeek</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>With this option On and the <b>Apache::Peek</b> module installed, functions and variables can be viewed ala <b>Devel::Peek</b> style:</p>

<pre class="sh_perl"> PerlSetVar StatusPeek On</pre>

<dt><a name="StatusLexInfo"
>StatusLexInfo</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>With this option On and the <b>B::LexInfo</b> module installed, subroutine lexical variable information can be viewed.</p>

<pre class="sh_perl"> PerlSetVar StatusLexInfo On</pre>

<dt><a name="StatusDeparse"
>StatusDeparse</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>With this option On and <b>B::Deparse</b> version 0.59 or higher (included in Perl 5.005_59+), subroutines can be &#34;deparsed&#34;.</p>

<pre class="sh_perl"> PerlSetVar StatusDeparse On</pre>

<p>Options can be passed to B::Deparse::new like so:</p>

<pre class="sh_perl"> PerlSetVar StatusDeparseOptions &#34;-p -sC&#34;</pre>

<p>See the <b>B::Deparse</b> manpage for details.</p>

<dt><a name="StatusTerse"
>StatusTerse</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>With this option On, text-based op tree graphs of subroutines can be displayed, thanks to <b>B::Terse</b>.</p>

<pre class="sh_perl"> PerlSetVar StatusTerse On</pre>

<dt><a name="StatusTerseSize"
>StatusTerseSize</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>With this option On and the <b>B::TerseSize</b> module installed, text-based op tree graphs of subroutines and their size can be displayed. See the <b>B::TerseSize</b> docs for more info.</p>

<pre class="sh_perl"> PerlSetVar StatusTerseSize On</pre>

<dt><a name="StatusTerseSizeMainSummary"
>StatusTerseSizeMainSummary</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>With this option On and the <b>B::TerseSize</b> module installed, a &#34;Memory Usage&#34; will be added to the Apache::Status main menu. This option is disabled by default, as it can be rather cpu intensive to summarize memory usage for the entire server. It is strongly suggested that this option only be used with a development server running in <b>-X</b> mode, as the results will be cached.</p>

<pre class="sh_perl"> PerlSetVar StatusTerseSizeMainSummary On</pre>

<dt><a name="StatusGraph"
>StatusGraph</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>When <b>StatusDumper</b> is enabled, another link &#34;OP Tree Graph&#34; will be present with the dump if this configuration variable is set to On:</p>

<pre class="sh_perl"> PerlSetVar StatusGraph</pre>

<p>This requires the B module (part of the Perl compiler kit) and B::Graph (version 0.03 or higher) module to be installed along with the <b>dot</b> program.</p>

<p>Dot is part of the graph visualization toolkit from AT&#38;T: <code><a href="http://www.research.att.com/sw/tools/graphviz/" class="podlinkurl"
>http://www.research.att.com/sw/tools/graphviz/</a></code>).</p>

<p><b>WARNING</b>: Some graphs may produce very large images, some graphs may produce no image if B::Graph&#39;s output is incorrect.</p>

<dt><a name="Dot"
>Dot</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>Location of the dot program for StatusGraph, if other than /usr/bin or /usr/local/bin</p>

<dt><a name="GraphDir"
>GraphDir</a></dt>

<dd>
<p>Directory where StatusGraph should write it&#39;s temporary image files. Default is $ServerRoot/logs/b_graphs</p>
</dd>
</dl>

